00:01:14.240 --> 00:01:17.250
then you choosing the quizzes
would very much be a commitment

00:01:17.250 --> 00:01:17.750
device.

00:01:17.750 --> 00:01:20.780
But if I sort of just
impose it on you,

00:01:20.780 --> 00:01:23.060
then, strictly
speaking, it is not,

00:01:23.060 --> 00:01:25.580
even though it sort of
functions in the exact same way

00:01:25.580 --> 00:01:28.570
as if you had chosen it.

00:01:28.570 --> 00:01:29.750
OK.

00:01:29.750 --> 00:01:32.630
Mostly we are discussing
empirical questions

00:01:32.630 --> 00:01:35.480
related to hyperbolic or
quasi-hyperbolic discounting.

00:01:35.480 --> 00:01:37.010
I want to have a
short intermezzo

00:01:37.010 --> 00:01:38.990
very briefly about
sort of telling you

00:01:38.990 --> 00:01:41.990
about how to solve problems with
quasi-hyperbolic discounting

00:01:41.990 --> 00:01:44.420
in part because that's
relevant to the problems set.

00:01:44.420 --> 00:01:46.280
I already talked
with you briefly

00:01:46.280 --> 00:01:48.800
about how do you deal
with fully naive agents

00:01:48.800 --> 00:01:51.770
and how do you deal with
fully sophisticated agents.

00:01:51.770 --> 00:01:54.620
In some sense, it's fairly
simple in these two cases,

00:01:54.620 --> 00:01:57.990
in part because these are
special extreme cases.

00:01:57.990 --> 00:02:03.540
Now, the third case
is, what do you

00:02:03.540 --> 00:02:05.700
do when you have a partially
naive decision-maker?

00:02:05.700 --> 00:02:08.009
And that's a little
trickier, and we

00:02:08.009 --> 00:02:10.440
tend to not have
that many problems

00:02:10.440 --> 00:02:12.790
related to partially
naive decision-makers.

00:02:12.790 --> 00:02:15.480
[INAUDIBLE] is a
little tricky to do.

00:02:15.480 --> 00:02:17.670
So essentially, what
you do is you kind of

00:02:17.670 --> 00:02:20.250
do the same as you do for
the fully sophisticated

00:02:20.250 --> 00:02:21.060
decision-maker.

00:02:21.060 --> 00:02:23.862
You do start by doing
backwards induction.

00:02:23.862 --> 00:02:25.320
You essentially
solve for what does

00:02:25.320 --> 00:02:28.950
the person think they're
going to do in the future.

00:02:28.950 --> 00:02:36.720
For that-- I'm speechless.

00:02:41.013 --> 00:02:46.890
For that, what do you do is
you use people's beta hat,

00:02:46.890 --> 00:02:49.920
and beta hat is essentially
what the person believes

00:02:49.920 --> 00:02:51.510
they will do in the future.

00:02:51.510 --> 00:02:55.050
And then, essentially, solve
using backwards induction what

00:02:55.050 --> 00:02:56.730
the person thinks they will do.

00:02:56.730 --> 00:02:58.290
This is the exact
same thing as you

00:02:58.290 --> 00:03:00.630
do for a sophisticated
person, except for that you're

00:03:00.630 --> 00:03:02.460
using now people's
beta hat as opposed

00:03:02.460 --> 00:03:04.428
to people's actual beta.

00:03:04.428 --> 00:03:06.720
The difference is, of course,
it's always the beta hat.

00:03:06.720 --> 00:03:09.120
It just happens to be for
the sophisticated person

00:03:09.120 --> 00:03:11.678
that the beta hat
actually is the beta.

00:03:11.678 --> 00:03:13.470
So then, essentially,
you start at the end.

00:03:13.470 --> 00:03:14.460
You do backwards induction.

00:03:14.460 --> 00:03:16.380
You go back in time,
work yourself [INAUDIBLE]

00:03:16.380 --> 00:03:18.735
period two, so then the
person using the beta hat

00:03:18.735 --> 00:03:20.610
knows what they're going
to do in the future,

00:03:20.610 --> 00:03:22.902
thinks they know what they're
going to do in the future

00:03:22.902 --> 00:03:24.607
starting in the next period.

00:03:24.607 --> 00:03:26.940
Then you're going to start
solving for the first period,

00:03:26.940 --> 00:03:29.040
like what is the person
actually going to do?

00:03:29.040 --> 00:03:31.190
For that, what you need is
the person's actual beta

00:03:31.190 --> 00:03:32.940
because that's essentially
what determines

00:03:32.940 --> 00:03:35.130
people's actual choices.

00:03:35.130 --> 00:03:36.780
And then you go
to the next period

00:03:36.780 --> 00:03:38.100
and do exactly the same thing.

00:03:38.100 --> 00:03:39.850
Again, you do sort of
backwards induction.

00:03:39.850 --> 00:03:43.950
You already have solved
that from the previous step.

00:03:43.950 --> 00:03:45.780
But then, essentially,
in period two,

00:03:45.780 --> 00:03:48.210
then, the person actually
uses again their actual beta

00:03:48.210 --> 00:03:49.980
for making their decisions.

00:03:49.980 --> 00:03:52.260
So the beta hats are
guiding people's beliefs

00:03:52.260 --> 00:03:54.340
about what they think they
will do in the future,

00:03:54.340 --> 00:03:56.048
but then you have to
go back and actually

00:03:56.048 --> 00:03:57.820
look at what does the
person actually do.

00:03:57.820 --> 00:04:00.900
And that often
differs, in particular

00:04:00.900 --> 00:04:03.780
when you get to like period two,
three, and four in the future.

00:04:07.480 --> 00:04:08.604
Sorry, this is not--

00:04:13.928 --> 00:04:15.470
The second thing I
wanted to say is--

00:04:15.470 --> 00:04:18.470
and this is mostly relevant
for problem set two.

00:04:18.470 --> 00:04:21.019
So far, we have essentially
looked at continuous choices.

00:04:21.019 --> 00:04:22.670
It's like going to
a movie versus not,

00:04:22.670 --> 00:04:24.680
or at some point you have
like one movie that you can go

00:04:24.680 --> 00:04:26.388
to which essentially
is sort of following

00:04:26.388 --> 00:04:29.420
the O'Donaghue-Rabin
papers and examples.

00:04:29.420 --> 00:04:31.977
You have one problem set you
need to do at some point.

00:04:31.977 --> 00:04:33.560
This is essentially
a discrete choice.

00:04:33.560 --> 00:04:35.720
Do you do it, or
do you not do it?

00:04:35.720 --> 00:04:38.780
Of course, many choices in
life so exactly like that,

00:04:38.780 --> 00:04:40.880
like, essentially, when
do you do the problem sets

00:04:40.880 --> 00:04:44.310
and so on and so forth,
but other choices in life

00:04:44.310 --> 00:04:47.210
are continuous consumption
savings or continuous choices.

00:04:47.210 --> 00:04:49.820
It's about like how much do you
eat, how much do you consume,

00:04:49.820 --> 00:04:51.810
and so on and so forth.

00:04:51.810 --> 00:04:54.200
And sort of the canonical
thing to do in economics

00:04:54.200 --> 00:04:55.740
are consumption savings choices.

00:04:55.740 --> 00:04:56.990
You have some amount of money.

00:04:56.990 --> 00:04:58.100
You think about
how much should you

00:04:58.100 --> 00:05:00.200
consume in this period,
how much should you save.

00:05:00.200 --> 00:05:01.040
There's an interest rate.

00:05:01.040 --> 00:05:03.082
You're going to get more
money than in the future

00:05:03.082 --> 00:05:05.360
if you save more and
so on and so forth.

00:05:05.360 --> 00:05:07.280
The same principles
here apply as well

00:05:07.280 --> 00:05:10.450
except for now you're not
comparing discrete choices,

00:05:10.450 --> 00:05:12.950
but now you do, essentially,
[INAUDIBLE] conditions the same

00:05:12.950 --> 00:05:16.040
what would you do in
any optimization problem

00:05:16.040 --> 00:05:18.860
as you would do in
1401 or one or any sort

00:05:18.860 --> 00:05:25.520
of intro micro class where,
essentially, you optimize

00:05:25.520 --> 00:05:27.770
using [INAUDIBLE]
conditions, et cetera,

00:05:27.770 --> 00:05:30.860
subject to some
budget constraint.

00:05:30.860 --> 00:05:33.200
In the recitation, you get
