00:06:11.070 --> 00:06:13.278
So then we're going to talk
about other applications,

00:06:13.278 --> 00:06:18.390
starting with credit card teaser
rates or credit card behavior.

00:06:18.390 --> 00:06:20.430
This is an old paper
by Ausubel [INAUDIBLE]..

00:06:20.430 --> 00:06:22.680
You can have any concerns
about it, but in some sense,

00:06:22.680 --> 00:06:27.360
it's sort of nicely illustrates
very simple behaviors

00:06:27.360 --> 00:06:29.880
that are very nicely fitting
into the quasi-hyperbolic

00:06:29.880 --> 00:06:31.140
discounting model.

00:06:31.140 --> 00:06:35.405
So this is evidence from using
real-world credit card usage.

00:06:35.405 --> 00:06:36.780
So essentially,
there's a company

00:06:36.780 --> 00:06:40.360
who has a bunch of data
on credit card usages,

00:06:40.360 --> 00:06:42.360
and as you might be aware,
credit card companies

00:06:42.360 --> 00:06:44.443
send out all sorts of
mailers about getting people

00:06:44.443 --> 00:06:46.080
to sign up for a credit card.

00:06:46.080 --> 00:06:49.830
In particular, once you're
out of school and gainfully

00:06:49.830 --> 00:06:52.920
employed, you get
all sorts of mailings

00:06:52.920 --> 00:06:55.365
and so on asking you to
sign up for credit cards.

00:06:58.470 --> 00:07:01.890
Now, in this particular
example, the company

00:07:01.890 --> 00:07:04.680
mailed out randomized
credit card offers

00:07:04.680 --> 00:07:06.060
of the following types.

00:07:06.060 --> 00:07:07.620
There was like a
standard credit card

00:07:07.620 --> 00:07:13.500
offer, which was a 6.9% interest
rate for six months and 16%

00:07:13.500 --> 00:07:16.530
afterwards, so there's already,
in some sense, a teaser rate

00:07:16.530 --> 00:07:18.810
built-in in the sense
it's starting to be looks

00:07:18.810 --> 00:07:20.140
like it's really cheap.

00:07:20.140 --> 00:07:23.880
You might sort of think, oh, I'm
going to just bar for a month,

00:07:23.880 --> 00:07:25.762
and then eventually,
it gets more expensive.

00:07:25.762 --> 00:07:27.220
The hope of the
company, of course,

00:07:27.220 --> 00:07:29.610
is that you keep borrowing
from them once it actually

00:07:29.610 --> 00:07:30.900
gets more expensive.

00:07:30.900 --> 00:07:33.090
And then there's two
randomized conditions.

00:07:33.090 --> 00:07:36.780
There's what they call
the teaser deal, which

00:07:36.780 --> 00:07:41.000
is 4.9% followed by
16%, and then there's

00:07:41.000 --> 00:07:42.750
what they call the
post-teaser deal, which

00:07:42.750 --> 00:07:46.080
is 6.9% followed by 4%.

00:07:46.080 --> 00:07:51.570
Notice that if you borrow a
given amount for quite a while

00:07:51.570 --> 00:07:54.540
and that these two conditions
are pretty much similar,

00:07:54.540 --> 00:07:56.640
depending a little bit
how long you borrow,

00:07:56.640 --> 00:07:59.040
if you borrow for
something like a year,

00:07:59.040 --> 00:08:00.892
then it's about
similar or the same.

00:08:00.892 --> 00:08:02.350
If you borrow for
more than a year,

00:08:02.350 --> 00:08:05.280
then you know option
three is probably better

00:08:05.280 --> 00:08:09.090
than option two for you for a
given amount that you borrow.

00:08:09.090 --> 00:08:11.880
But what the company
then has is response rate

00:08:11.880 --> 00:08:17.310
and people's 20-month borrowing
history for individuals

00:08:17.310 --> 00:08:18.205
who take up the card.

00:08:18.205 --> 00:08:19.830
Now, these are kind
of selected, so you

00:08:19.830 --> 00:08:22.080
want to be a little bit
careful how to interpret that.

00:08:22.080 --> 00:08:25.452
But the response rates
surely are the right thing

00:08:25.452 --> 00:08:27.660
to look at because they'd
be randomized across people

00:08:27.660 --> 00:08:29.040
who read which letter.

00:08:29.040 --> 00:08:31.890
What they find is
that the response rate

00:08:31.890 --> 00:08:36.000
is about 2.5 times
larger increase

00:08:36.000 --> 00:08:39.240
in take-up in the second
relative to the third group.

00:08:39.240 --> 00:08:41.580
Now, given subsequent
borrowing behavior-- and that's

00:08:41.580 --> 00:08:42.480
kind of endogenous.

00:08:42.480 --> 00:08:44.397
You want to be a little
bit careful with that.

00:08:44.397 --> 00:08:46.830
But essentially, if you
look at people's behavior,

00:08:46.830 --> 00:08:49.687
the latter is a
much better deal.

00:08:49.687 --> 00:08:51.270
So you'd much rather
have-- as I said,

00:08:51.270 --> 00:08:55.590
you'd much rather have like
deal number three compared

00:08:55.590 --> 00:08:56.460
to deal number two.

00:08:56.460 --> 00:08:59.160
And particularly, if you
borrow for, say, two years

00:08:59.160 --> 00:09:02.180
like $1,000, you're going
to pay much more interest

00:09:02.180 --> 00:09:06.370
in deal number two
compared to number three.

00:09:06.370 --> 00:09:08.677
Yes?

00:09:08.677 --> 00:09:11.010
Now how do we think about
this from the quasi-hyperbolic

00:09:11.010 --> 00:09:11.790
discounting model?

00:09:11.790 --> 00:09:13.123
How do we explain this behavior?

00:09:25.690 --> 00:09:26.501
Yes?

